          <exercise>
            <title>A question about the slope-intercept form of the equation of a line</title>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Recall that the slope-intercept form of the equation of a line is <m>y=mx+b</m>
                    where <m>m</m> is the slope of the line and <m>b</m> is the <m>y</m>-coordinate
                    of the <m>y</m>-intercept of the line.  Use this information to determine 
                    the slope-intercept form of the equation of the line shown in 
                    <xref ref="line-1">Figure</xref>.
                  </p> 
                </statement>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    The equation is <m>y=\frac{3}{2}x+2</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
          </exercise> 

