          <exercise>
            <title>A question about the slope-intercept form of the equation of a line</title>
                <statement>
                  <p>
                    Determine the slope-intercept form of the equation of the line that passes through
                    the points <m>(2,-2)</m> and <m>(0,3)</m>.  Use the Desmos graph to confirm your
                    equation.
                  </p> 
                </statement>
                <solution>
                  <p>
                    We begin by using the formula <m>m=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</m>.
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    <m>m=\frac{3-(-2)}{0-2}=-\frac{5}{2}</m>
                  </p>
                  <p>
                    We know that the <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,3)</m>, so the slope-intercept
                    equation for the line is <m>y=-\frac{5}{2}x+3</m>.
                  </p>
                </solution>
          </exercise> 

          <exercise>
            <title>A question about the slope-intercept form of the equation of a line</title>
                <statement>
                  <sidebyside widths="67% 27%" margins="0%">
                    <p>
                      Determine the slope-intercept equation for the line that passes through 
                      the points shown in <xref ref="table-3-1">Table</xref>.
                    </p>

                    <table xml:id="table-3-1">
                      <caption></caption>
                        <tabular>
                          <col halign="center" />
                          <col halign="center"/>
                          <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>x</m></line>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>y</m></line>
                            </cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>-7</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                          </row>
                        </tabular>
                      </table>
                    </sidebyside> 
                  </statement>
                  <solution>
                    <p>
                      We begin by using the formula <m>m=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</m> to determine that the slope
                      of the line is <m>-3</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      We don't directly know the <m>y</m>-intercept of the line, but from the slope we know
                      that the equation of the line is <m>y=-3x+b</m> where <m>b</m> is the 
                      <m>y</m>-coordinate of the <m>y</m>-intercept.  Plugging the ordered pair <m>(2,-7)</m> into
                      that equation gives us <m>-7=(-3)(2)+b</m>, and solving for <m>b</m> we get
                      <m>-1</m>, so the slope-intercept equation for the line is <m>y=-3x-1</m>.  Note that we could also have used the ordered pair <m>(-3,8)</m> to determine the
                      value of <m>b</m>.
                    </p>
                 </solution>
          </exercise> 

          <exercise>
            <title>A question about the slope-intercept form of the equation of a line</title>
                <statement>
                  <sidebyside widths="67% 27%" margins="0%">
                    <p>
                      Determine the slope-intercept equation for the line that passes through 
                      the points shown in <xref ref="table-3-2">Table</xref>.
                    </p>

                    <table xml:id="table-3-2">
                      <caption></caption>
                        <tabular>
                          <col halign="center" />
                          <col halign="center"/>
                          <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>x</m></line>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>y</m></line>
                            </cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>-3</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>1</m></cell>
                          </row>
                        </tabular>
                      </table>
                    </sidebyside> 
                  </statement>
                  <solution>
                    <p>
                      We begin by using the formula <m>m=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}</m> to determine that the slope
                      of the line is <m>-\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                    </p>
                    <p>
                      We don't directly know the <m>y</m>-intercept of the line, but from the slope we know
                      that the equation of the line is <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+b</m> where <m>b</m> is the 
                      <m>y</m>-coordinate of the <m>y</m>-intercept.  Plugging the ordered pair <m>(5,1)</m> into
                      that equation gives us <m>1=-\frac{1}{2}(5)+b</m>, and solving for <m>b</m> we get
                      <m>b=\frac{7}{2}</m>, so the slope-intercept equation for the line is <m>y=-\frac{1}{2}x+\frac{7}{2}</m>.  Note that we could also have used the ordered pair <m>(-3,5)</m> to determine the
                      value of <m>b</m>.
                    </p>
                 </solution>
          </exercise> 

           <exercise>
            <title>A question about linear behavior</title>
                <statement>
                  <sidebyside widths="67% 27%" margins="0%">
                    <p>
                      Explain why the three points shown in <xref ref="table-3-3">Table</xref>
                      cannot possibly all lie on the same line.
                    </p>

                    <table xml:id="table-3-3">
                      <caption></caption>
                        <tabular>
                          <col halign="center" />
                          <col halign="center"/>
                          <row bottom="medium">
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>x</m></line>
                            </cell>
                            <cell>
                              <line><m>y</m></line>
                            </cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>12</m></cell>
                          </row>
                          <row>
                            <cell><m>8</m></cell>
                            <cell><m>19</m></cell>
                          </row>
                        </tabular>
                      </table>
                    </sidebyside> 
                  </statement>
                  <solution>
                    <p>
                      The line that passes through the first two points has a slope of <m>\frac{5}{3}</m> 
                      whereas the line that passes through the first and third point has a slope of
                      <m>2</m>.  If the points all lied on the same line, we would get the same slope
                      no matter which two points we used in the slope formula. 
                    </p>
                  </solution>
          </exercise> 
 
